# If Paris Were Told to Us (1956 film)

*Si Paris nous était conté* (original [French](/French_language) title, translating to "If [Paris](/Paris) Were Told to Us"), is a cinematic endeavor from 1956 that attempts nothing less than a grand historical tapestry of the French capital. Directed and penned by the inimitable, and some might say, relentlessly prolific, [Sacha Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry), this film invites audiences to witness the sprawling chronicle of [Paris](/Paris) from its nascent beginnings through centuries of transformation. It’s a bold undertaking, even for [Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry), to condense such a monumental history into a single feature, and one that only he, with his particular brand of theatrical flair and historical obsession, would even attempt.

The film serves as a sprawling historical fresco, charting the evolution of the city that has, for better or worse, become synonymous with French identity itself. Released on January 27, 1956, *If [Paris](/Paris) Were Told to Us* garnered a substantial audience in its home country, attracting 2,813,682 admissions in France alone. This figure speaks to the enduring fascination with the city and, perhaps more acutely, with [Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry)'s unique narrative voice.

## Production and Release

*Si Paris nous était conté* was a significant production for its time, with a budget reportedly reaching $3 million. This substantial sum allowed for the elaborate period recreations and the assembly of a truly star-studded cast, a hallmark of [Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry)'s later historical epics. The film was a collaborative effort between several production companies, including Courts et Longs Métrages (C.L.M.), F.L.F., and the venerable Société Nouvelle des Établissements [Gaumont](/Gaumont_Film_Company) (SNEG). Distribution was handled by Société des Etablissements L. Gaumont, ensuring a wide release across France.

The directorial reins, as well as the pen that shaped the narrative, belonged entirely to [Sacha Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry), a figure who often preferred to be the sole architect of his cinematic visions. The film's visual language was crafted by cinematographer [Philippe Agostini](/Philippe_Agostini), whose work brought the historical epochs to life with a suitable grandeur. Editing duties were meticulously performed by Paulette Robert, tasked with weaving together centuries of history into a coherent, flowing narrative. The musical score, an essential component for any historical epic, was composed by [Jean Françaix](/Jean_Fran%C3%A7aix), providing an auditory backdrop that aimed to evoke the spirit of each depicted era.

The film premiered on January 27, 1956, captivating audiences for its extensive running time of 130 minutes. Its reception in France, as evidenced by its robust box office performance of 2,813,682 admissions, underscored the enduring appeal of both [Paris](/Paris) and [Sacha Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry)'s distinctive approach to storytelling.

## Summary

*If Paris Were Told to Us* is not merely a historical film; it is [Sacha Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry)'s personal, often idiosyncratic, journey through the annals of the French capital. From the very founding of the city, shrouded in the mists of antiquity, to the pivotal events that irrevocably shaped its character, the film endeavors to capture the essence of [Paris](/Paris) across millennia.

The entire sprawling narrative is, quite fittingly, narrated by [Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry) himself, imbuing the historical account with his characteristic wit, erudition, and a certain theatrical grandiosity. He guides the audience through a selective, yet remarkably ambitious, panorama of French history, focusing on the historical figures whose lives and decisions left an indelible mark on the city. The film moves with a relentless pace, traversing centuries as it brings to life figures ranging from the pragmatic and often beleaguered [King Charles VII](/Charles_VII_of_France), who reigned during the tumultuous Hundred Years' War, to the ill-fated [King Henry III](/Henry_III_of_France), whose assassination in 1589 plunged France into further chaos during the Wars of Religion.

Beyond the shifting fortunes of monarchs, [Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry)'s narrative also highlights monumental cultural and architectural milestones. The revolutionary advent of printing, a technology that democratized knowledge and forever changed the intellectual landscape of [Paris](/Paris) and beyond, is explored for its profound impact. Similarly, the film traces the architectural evolution of the city, including the construction of the magnificent [Louvre Palace](/Louvre_Palace), which began as a medieval fortress and transformed into one of the world's most iconic museums and royal residences. Through these interwoven threads of personal drama, political intrigue, and cultural innovation, *If Paris Were Told to Us* endeavors to illustrate, with [Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry)'s unique flourish, how the French capital truly came to be the iconic global city it remains. It's an ambitious claim, of course, to fully encapsulate such a storied past, but [Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry) certainly makes a compelling, if theatrical, attempt.

## Principal Cast

The film boasts an impressive ensemble of French cinematic talent, a testament to [Sacha Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry)'s drawing power and the prestige associated with a project of this scale. Each actor, often portraying multiple historical figures, contributes to the vibrant tapestry of [Parisian](/Paris) history.

*   [Françoise Arnoul](/Fran%C3%A7oise_Arnoul) as Duchesse de L...: A prominent actress of the era, [Arnoul](/Fran%C3%A7oise_Arnoul) brought a sophisticated charm to her roles.
*   [Jeanne Boitel](/Jeanne_Boitel) as [Mme Geoffrin](/Marie_Th%C3%A9r%C3%A8se_Rodet_Geoffrin) / [Sarah Bernhardt](/Sarah_Bernhardt): [Boitel](/Jeanne_Boitel) takes on the dual challenge of portraying [Marie Thérèse Rodet Geoffrin](/Marie_Th%C3%A9r%C3%A8se_Rodet_Geoffrin), a leading figure of the Enlightenment salons, and the legendary actress [Sarah Bernhardt](/Sarah_Bernhardt), two women who profoundly influenced [Parisian](/Paris) intellectual and artistic life.
*   [Gilbert Bokanowski](/Gilbert_Bokanowski) as [Louis XVI](/Louis_XVI): [Bokanowski](/Gilbert_Bokanowski) embodies the ill-fated monarch whose reign culminated in the French Revolution.
*   [Julien Carette](/Julien_Carette) as Un cocher: A character actor renowned for his distinctive voice and often comedic roles, [Carette](/Julien_Carette) provides a grounding, everyday presence amidst the grand historical figures.
*   [Danielle Darrieux](/Danielle_Darrieux) as [Agnès Sorel](/Agn%C3%A8s_Sorel): The elegant and enduring star [Danielle Darrieux](/Danielle_Darrieux) portrays [Agnès Sorel](/Agn%C3%A8s_Sorel), the influential mistress of [King Charles VII](/Charles_VII_of_France), a figure whose beauty and political sway were legendary.
*   [Sophie Desmarets](/Sophie_Desmarets) as Rose Bertin: [Desmarets](/Sophie_Desmarets) steps into the shoes of Rose Bertin, the celebrated milliner and fashion advisor to [Marie-Antoinette](/Marie-Antoinette), a true icon of [Parisian](/Paris) haute couture.
*   [Clément Duhour](/Cl%C3%A9ment_Duhour) as [Aristide Bruant](/Aristide_Bruant): [Duhour](/Cl%C3%Aément_Duhour) brings to life [Aristide Bruant](/Aristide_Bruant), the famed singer and cabaret owner, synonymous with the bohemian nightlife of late 19th-century Montmartre.
*   [Sacha Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry) as [Louis XI](/Louis_XI): The director himself, [Sacha Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry), takes on the role of [Louis XI](/Louis_XI), the cunning and pragmatic "Spider King" who consolidated royal power in the 15th century.
*   [Odette Joyeux](/Odette_Joyeux) as La Passementiere: [Joyeux](/Odette_Joyeux) portrays a lacemaker, representing the skilled artisans who formed the backbone of [Parisian](/Paris) craftsmanship.
*   [Robert Lamoureux](/Robert_Lamoureux) as Latude: [Lamoureux](/Robert_Lamoureux) plays Latude, a man famous for his multiple escapes from the Bastille, a symbol of resistance against royal arbitrary power.
*   [Jacques Dumesnil](/Jacques_Dumesnil) as [Cardinal Richelieu](/Cardinal_Richelieu): [Dumesnil](/Jacques_Dumesnil) embodies the formidable [Cardinal Richelieu](/Cardinal_Richelieu), chief minister to [Louis XIII](/Louis_XIII) and a towering figure in French political history.
*   [Pierre Larquey](/Pierre_Larquey) as Pierre Broussel: [Larquey](/Pierre_Larquey) portrays Pierre Broussel, a member of the Parlement of [Paris](/Paris) whose arrest sparked the Fronde rebellion.
*   [Jean Marais](/Jean_Marais) as François Ier: The iconic [Jean Marais](/Jean_Marais), known for his heroic and romantic roles, depicts [François Ier](/Jean_Marais), the Renaissance king who brought unprecedented artistic and cultural flourishing to France.
*   [Jean Martinelli](/Jean_Martinelli) as [Henri IV](/Henri_IV) / Firmin: [Martinelli](/Jean_Martinelli) takes on the role of [Henri IV](/Henri_IV), the popular "Good King Henry" who ended the Wars of Religion and laid the foundations for a more unified France.
*   [Lana Marconi](/Lana_Marconi) as La reine [Marie-Antoinette](/Marie-Antoinette): [Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry)'s final wife, [Lana Marconi](/Lana_Marconi), portrays the tragic queen [Marie-Antoinette](/Marie-Antoinette), whose life and death are inextricably linked to the French Revolution and the fate of [Paris](/Paris).
*   [Michèle Morgan](/Mich%C3%A8le_Morgan) as Gabrielle d'Estrées: The luminous [Michèle Morgan](/Mich%C3%A8le_Morgan) plays Gabrielle d'Estrées, the beautiful and influential mistress of [Henri IV](/Henri_IV).
*   [Jean Parédès](/Jean_Par%C3%A9d%C3%A8s) as Un médecin: [Parédès](/Jean_Par%C3%A9d%C3%A8s) offers a glimpse into the medical practices of the past, often a source of [Guitry](/Sacha_Guitry)'s wry humor.
*   [Giselle Pascal](/Giselle_Pascal) as Comtesse de G...: [Pascal](/Giselle_Pascal) adds to the aristocratic presence, representing the countless noble figures who populated [Parisian](/Paris) society.
*   [Gérard Philipe](/G%C3%Aérard_Philipe) as Le Trouvère: The legendary [Gérard Philipe](/G%C3%Aérard_Philipe), known for his intense and charismatic performances, plays a Trouvère, a medieval poet-musician, embodying the artistic spirit that has always defined [Paris](/Paris).
*   [Odile Rodin](/Odile_Rodin) as the Princess of Essling: [Rodin](/Odile_Rodin) contributes to the depiction of royal and imperial court life.
*   [Claude Sylvain](/Claude_Sylvain) as Catherine de Médicis jeune: [Sylvain](/Claude_Sylvain) portrays a younger version of Catherine de Médicis, the powerful and often controversial queen consort and regent of France.